This confirms my finding. In `extended.c` (line 224) and `sasl.c` (line 302), the code correctly checks `if ( ber == NULL )` after `ber_dup()` before using `ber` in `ber_scanf`. But in `error.c` line 300-354, there is NO such NULL check after `ber_dup()` before calling `ber_scanf`.

The pattern in both `extended.c` and `sasl.c`:
```c
ber = ber_dup( res->lm_ber );
if ( ber == NULL ) {            // <-- NULL check PRESENT
    ld->ld_errno = LDAP_NO_MEMORY;
    return ld->ld_errno;
}
... ber_scanf( ber, ... ) ...  // Safe because of the NULL check
```

But in `error.c` `ldap_parse_result`, the code duplicates the BER structure and immediately attempts to scan it without checking if the duplication succeeded, creating a potential null pointer dereference vulnerability.

The pattern is inconsistent with other parts of the same library like `extended.c` and `sasl.c`, which properly guard against NULL returns from `ber_dup()`. The fact that a NULL check appears later at line 361 suggests the developer knew `ber_dup()` could fail, but failed to handle it before attempting to use the pointer in the scanning operations. `, ...)` crashes the LDAP client process. I notice that sibling functions in `sasl.c` and `extended.c` properly check for NULL after `ber_dup()`, confirming this is a known pattern the codebase should follow. An attacker controlling an LDAP server could exhaust client memory through repeated large responses, then send a valid result that triggers the allocation failure and null pointer dereference.

